abstract: Reading, watching and listening with California’s attorney general.
snippet: Reading, watching and listening with California’s attorney general.
lead_paragraph: Kamala Harris is California’s attorney general and the first woman of African and South Asian descent to serve in that position. She recently wrested $18 billion from financial institutions accused of mortgage misdeeds for her state’s beleaguered homeowners.

abstract: Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have become major residential landowners in the Bay Area, and some complain that they are hurting neighborhoods by not keeping all of their properties in good repair.

lead_paragraph: Every few weeks, Alvin Chandra cleans up the garbage that has accumulated in the vacant lot next to his granite fabrication plant on Adeline Street in West Oakland — soiled mattresses, worn-out sofa beds and piles of used fast food containers.

lead_paragraph: Bending the Tax Code, and Lifting A.I.G.’s Profit  |  Last week, the American International Group reported a whopping $19.8 billion profit for its fourth quarter. It was a quite a feat for a company that was on its death bed just a little over three years ago, so sick that it needed a huge taxpayer bailout, Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in his DealBook column.

abstract: As an economic concept, “moral hazard” means that people are apt to take undue risks if they don’t have to bear the consequences. But it’s also part of the debate on the limits of self-reliance.

abstract: California’s attorney general, Kamala D. Harris, said the state had reached an agreement with Amazon.com, Apple, Google, Hewlett-Packard, Microsoft and Research in Motion to strengthen privacy protections for smartphone owners who download mobile applications. The agreement will force developers to post conspicuous privacy policies.
